 Mayhem<br />Nytewalkers<br />Ghostly Glow Party<br />Opening Scares<br />Sideshow\n|\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| 11 || 2018\n| Madame Marie's Blackout<br />Zombie High<br />Backwoods<br />CornStalkers<br />Chaos House<br />Toy Factory<br />Roadkill Roadhouse<br />Wax Museum Chamber of Horrors<br />Tooth Fairy\n| Feary Tales<br>JesterTown<br>Ripper's Revenge\n| Blood Drums<br />Ed Alonzo, the Second Greatest Showman<br />Nytewalkers<br />Ghostly Glow Party<br />Opening Scares<br />Sideshow\n|\n|}\n\n==California's Great America's timeline==\n[[File:Aerial view of California's Great America 3.JPG|right|thumb|Water slides viewed from the cable car]]\n[[Image:Invertigo.jpg|thumb|The former Invertigo coaster (Removed 2011)]]\n[[Image:Invertigo At Great America.jpg|thumb|right|Complete View of the former Invertigo coaster]]\n* 2020: Boomerang Bay expanded and renamed [[South Bay Shores]]\n* 2019: Drop Tower gets a new paint scheme to represent a Redwood Tree. Pre-K pass is introduced for the 2019 season. \n* 2018: RailBlazer, one of the world's first Raptor Track Coasters by [[Rocky Mountain Construction]]. Halloween Haunt and WinterFest expansions.\n* 2017: Patriot, a floorless conversion, repaint and re-theme of the park's stand-up coaster, Vortex. Halloween Haunt and Winterfest expansions. Sweet Tooth, funnel cake shop, FireFall, Logger's Run, H.M.B Endevour and Snoopy's Splash Dance are removed.\n* 2016: A 4D holographic attraction themed to BioWare's [[Mass Effect]] video game in newly renovated Action Theater. Winterfest debuts. Halloween Haunt expansion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagreatamerica.com/what-s-new/coming-in-2016|title=Great America Announces New Attraction Featuring Mass Effect Videogame Series for 2016|publisher=California's Great America|accessdate=September 30, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/entertainment/ci_28896052/great-america-electronic-arts-creating-mass-effects-attraction|title=Great America, Electronic Arts creating 'Mass Effects' attraction|last=Zavoral|first=Linda|date=September 29, 2015|work=San Jose Mercury News|accessdate=September 30, 2015}}</ref>\n* 2015: Planet Snoopy takes over the former KidZville section of the park. Halloween Haunt expansion.\n* 2014: Flight Deck re-painted red and white, Grizzly Loading Dock painted red and white, Fun TV added to most rides, Grizzly re-tracked and new flooring in Carousel Columbia. Halloween Haunt expansion. Picnic Pavilion make-over and new entrance from the parking lot. All 6 Drop Tower cabins operating, and KidzVille Shooting Range removed for birthday party area. All Day Dining Pass and new food options added. Halloween Haunt expansion with more monsters, two new Haunted Mazes for 2014, and one new Haunted Attraction. Werewolf Canyon and Slaughterhouse: Annihilation mazes removed. The Overlord is removed as Haunt icon. Skeleton Key is added, giving 5 mazes a new interactive room.<ref>{{cite web |date=March 8, 2014 |title=Off season tour and 2014 season details |publisher=Park Valley |url=http://cgaintel.blogspot.com/2014/03/off-season-tour-and-2014-season-details.html#more}}</ref>\n* 2013: New [[Great Coasters International]] wooden coaster, \"[[Gold Striker]]\" added; Happy Feet: Mumble's Wild Ride in the Action Theater; Subway added, Halloween Haunt expansion.\n* 2012: Several park improvements such as a repaint of Carousel Columbia, Demon and Flight Deck. ADA improvements including an elevator lift entrance for Loggers Run and Vortex. Also, The Grizzly is retracked, [[Fast Lane (Cedar Fair)|Fast Lane]]. Construction commenced on [[Levi's Stadium]], the new home of the [[San Francisco 49ers]], in the former Great America overflow parking lot. Halloween Haunt expansion,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.49ers.com/2012/04/02/stadium-groundbreaking-slated-for-april-19/ |title=49ers.com &#124; Stadium Groundbreaking Slated for April 19 |publisher=Blog.49ers.com |accessdate=2012-06-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625211803/http://blog.49ers.com/2012/04/02/stadium-groundbreaking-slated-for-april-19/ |archivedate=June 25, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Construction of 2013 attraction, [[Gold Striker]] (wooden coaster), in former Whizzer site.\n* 2011: Invertigo is removed to be sent to [[Dorney Park]]; Three new live shows. Halloween Haunt Expansion.\n* 2010: Planet Snoopy (Retheme of Nickelodeon Central); Hanna Barbera references removed in KidZville; Panda Express\n* 2009: All Wheels Extreme Stunt show; Chipper Lowell Experience show; expanded Halloween Haunt\n* 2008: Park is renamed to '''California's Great America'''; FireFall; Dora's Sing-Along Adventure; Endless Summer On Ice show; Halloween Haunt debuts\n* 2007: Park is renamed to '''Great America'''; Great Barrier Reef Wavepool added to Boomerang Bay; [[Ed Alonzo]] Misfit of Magic; Twistin' to the '60s Show\n* 2006: Tiki Twirl (Formerly Survivor: The Ride); Park is sold to Cedar Fair\n* 2005: Boomerang Bay expansion to include lazy river, two other waterslides and a large swimming pool.\n* 2004: Boomerang Bay is added including a complex of children's water slides/play area, a 4-person adult raft/tube ride, a two-person inner-tube water slide and a fully enclosed two-person inner-tube water slide. Triple Play is removed\n* 2003: SpongeBob SquarePants 3-D in the Action Theater; [[Nickelodeon Central]] (expansion of Splat City); Stealth (flying steel coaster) is removed and sent to [[Carowinds]] as Nighthawk\n* 2002: Delirium; Flying Eagles; Greased Lightning (shuttle loop coaster) is removed; Time Capsule buried\n* 2001: Psycho Mouse; Celebration Swings; Thunder Raceway; Stan Lee's 7th Portal 3D/ Smash Factory in Action Theater\n* 2000: Stealth (flying steel coaster) opens to the public; Scenic Railroad and Skyhawk are removed\n* 1999: KidZVille; Tidal Wave renamed Greased Lightnin'; Stealth is constructed and tested all season; Logger's Run modified to allow construction of Stealth\n* 1998: Invertigo; James Bond: License to Thrill;<ref name=\"hq.usace.army.mil\"/> in the Paramount Action F/X Theater Yankee Clipper is removed\n* 1997: Xtreme Skyflyer; Triple Wheel (originally Sky Whirl) is removed\n* 1996: Drop Tower Scream Zone (Formerly Drop Zone Stunt Tower)\n* 1995: [[Nickelodeon Splat City]]; The Edge and Ameri- Go Round are removed.\n* 1994: Action Theater featuring Days of Thunder\n* 1993: Park is renamed '''Paramount's Great America'''; Flight Deck (Formerly Top Gun); Lobster is removed\n* 1992: KECO is acquired by Paramount, and renamed Paramount Parks; IMAX Pictorium Theater received a $1.5 million upgrade allowing it to screen 3-D films.\n* 1991: Vortex; Saskatchewan Scrambler is removed. \n* 1990: Whitewater Falls\n* 1989: Skyhawk; Park is acquired by KECO from the City of Santa Clara; Dolphin and Seal show and Cajun Carpet are removed.\n* 1988: Rip Roaring Rapids. Whizzer and Bottom's Up are removed\n* 1987: Woodstock Express (Formerly Blue Streak/ Green Slime Mine Car Coaster/ Runaway Reptar); Smurf Woods; Fort Fun; HMB Endeavor (Formerly known as The Revolution)\n* 1986: The Grizzly; Redwood Amphitheater with the ''Miami Sound Machine''\n* 1985: Park is renamed '''Great America.'''\n* 1984: Park is sold by Marriott corporation to the City of Santa Clara; management transfers to Kings Entertainment Company (KECO); Hilltopper is removed.\n* 1983: The Edge; Red Baron and Ladybugs are removed.\n* 1982: Atari Video Adventure\n* 1980: The Demon (remodeled from Turn of the Century); Gulf coaster is removed\n* 1979: Star Tower (formerly Sky Tower)\n* 1978: IMAX Pictorium Theater, with film ''Man Belongs to the Earth''\n* 1977: Tidal Wave\n* 1976: '''Marriott's Great America''' opens\n\n==On film and television==\n===Beverly Hills Cop III===\nThough appearing under the name \"Wonder World\", Paramount's Great America was used for exterior scenes of the theme park in the 1994 film ''[[Beverly Hills Cop III]]'' (itself released by Paramount Pictures) after [[Knott's Berry Farm]] declined filming rights.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/1993/voices/columns/cop-iii-displays-spectacle-for-wasserman-1117862394/ |title='Cop III' displays spectacle for Wasserman |author=Archerd, Army |author-link=Army Archerd |date=December 13, 1993 |work=Variety |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-xpm-1994-05-25-9405240754-story.html |title='Cop III': Eddie rides again |author=Boyar, Jay |date=May 25, 1994 |newspaper=Orlando Sentinel |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nWriter Steven E. de Souza originally wrote the story as more \"Die Hard in a theme park\". He was told that each of the rides he had designed would cost about $10 million to build and the whole film would cost about $70 million. When box office results for ''[[The Distinguished Gentleman]]'' came in, Paramount ordered the budget to be cut to $55 million.\n\nSome modifications were made to the Columbia Carousel and Vortex roller coaster. Most of the Sky Whirl/Triple Wheel stunts (renamed \"The Spider\" for the film) were filmed in a studio. To film the exterior scenes, the motors of the Triple Wheel were left unpowered; instead, to ensure the ride did not move too quickly, some cages were loaded with sandbags to unbalance the mechanism.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://ew.com/article/1994/06/10/eddie-murphys-dangerous-ride/ |title=Eddie Murphy's dangerous ride |author=Mannes, George |date=June 10, 1994 |work=Entertainment Weekly |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref> In this scene, [[George Lucas]] has a small part as the man Axel cuts in front of to get on the ride, also known as 'disappointed man' (this can be seen in the credits). [[John Singleton]] and [[Martha Coolidge]] also made cameo appearances in the film.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19940525&slug=1912261 |title='Cop III': Though Murphy's A Draw, There Oughta Be A Law |author=Shannon, Jeff |date=May 25, 1994 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nMany rides that were seen in the movie including Triple Play/Sky Whirl have since been removed. Also, the carousel at the back of the park (the Ameri-Go-Round, not the Columbia Carousel) was altered. The Ameri-Go-Round carousel has since been removed and Drop Zone is now in its place. The tunnels that supposedly ran under the park are a myth as well. No tunnels run under the park, as many thought after this was released.\n\nThe Alien Attack ride featured in the Wonder World theme park was in fact the \"Earthquake: The Big One attraction\" from the [[Universal Studios Florida]] theme park in [[Orlando, Florida]]. The \"aliens\" featured in the ride are suited actors (and not animatronic as suggested in the film) that closely resembled the Cylons from the original Battlestar Galactica.<ref name=TPI-131116>{{cite web |url=https://www.themeparkinsider.com/flume/201311/3778/ |title=Theme Park History: 10 top movies or TV shows filmed in theme parks |author=Potter, Derek |date=November 16, 2013 |website=Theme Park Insider |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Other film and television===\n* Paramount's Great America was also used as the theme park [[Macaulay Culkin]] visits in the 1994 film ''[[Getting Even with Dad]]'' (not released by Paramount Pictures but rather [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://greatamericanthrills.net/2014/08/24/getting-even-with-dad-filmed-at-californias-great-america/ |title=Getting Even With Dad Filmed at California's Great America |author=Rowberry, Kris |date=August 24, 2014 |website=Great American Thrills |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n* The park's inverted steel coaster \"Top Gun\" (later renamed to \"Flight Deck\") was featured in a 2007 [[Excedrin]] commercial with music from [[The Stremes]].<ref>{{youtube |id=Nw-d5OZOWA0 |title=Excedrin TV Advert - Music by The Stremes}}</ref>\n* Marriott's Great America was used in the 1983 George Lucas and [[John Korty]] animated feature [[Twice Upon a Time (1983 film)|''Twice Upon A Time'']].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/MovieDetails/58153 |title=Twice Upon a Time (1983) |publisher=AFI Catalog of Feature Films |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref> It was used both as a background for animated scenes and for a short live-action shot at the end of the film.\n\n==Incidents==\n{{Main|Incidents at Cedar Fair parks}}\n* In 1980, a 13-year-old boy was killed and several others injured on the [[Whizzer (roller coaster)|Willard's Whizzer]] roller coaster. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2015/06/13/previous-accidents-at-great-america/|title=Previous accidents at Great America|last=Kaplan|first=Tracy|date=June 13, 2015|work=San Jose Mercury News|access-date=March 15, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* In 1989, two boys intentionally jumped out of the Loggers' Run ride. One was killed and the other fell onto a platform and was injured.<ref name=\"abc7news.com: 7/12/07\">{{cite web |last=Rosales |first=Erik |url=http://abclocal.go.com/kgo/story?section=local&id=5476441 |title=[Title lost before link went dead] |publisher=KGO-TV |date=2007-07-12 |accessdate=2012-06-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080305235532/http://abclocal.go.com/kgo/story?section=local&id=5476441 |archivedate=March 5, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* In 1998, after riding [[Flight Deck (California's Great America)|Flight Deck]], a 24-year-old Spanish-speaking man, who could not read the English-language warning signs, entered a locked, gated area underneath the ride to retrieve his hat. He was hit by the foot of a passenger on the Flight Deck train and later died. The passenger suffered a broken leg.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rideaccidents.com/1998.html |title=1998 News Archive: Roller coaster accident kills a man in California |publisher=Rideaccidents.com |date=September 7, 1998 |accessdate=2012-06-04 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420021129/http://rideaccidents.com/1998.html#sep7 |archivedate=April 20, 2017 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* In 1999, a 12-year-old boy fell to his death on '''Drop Tower''' after slipping from the ride's restraints, which were still locked at the end of the ride.<ref>{{cite news\n|publisher = Courier-Journal |date = June 23, 2007 |url=http://www.courier-journal.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?Date=20071129&Category=NEWS01&ArtNo=111290002&SectionCat=&Template=printart |title = Thrill ride lawsuits |accessdate =November 4, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rideaccidents.com/1999.html|title=Drop Zone death: no charges, no explanation|date=November 5, 1999|publisher=RideAccidents.com|accessdate=December 4, 2011|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420021130/http://www.rideaccidents.com/1999.html#nov5|archivedate=April 20, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* On July 12, 2007, a 4-year-old boy drowned in the Boomerang Bay's Great Barrier Reef [[wave pool]].<ref name=\"abc7news.com: 7/12/07\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbc11.com/news/13672880/detail.html |title=4-Year-Old Drowns In California's Great America Wave Pool&nbsp;\u2013 News Story&nbsp;\u2013 KNTV &#124; San Francisco |publisher=Nbc11.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-04}}</ref>\n* On June 12, 2015, a maintenance worker was critically injured after being struck in the head by a moving train on [[Flight Deck (California's Great America)|Flight Deck]]. A passenger sustained serious hand and leg injuries in the incident.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mercurynews.com/california/ci_28306406/great-america-roller-coaster-accident-injures-two-people%7D%7D|title=Great America roller coaster accident injures two people|last1=Kaplan|first1=Tracy|last2=Nelson|first2=Katie|date=June 13, 2015|work=San Jose Mercury News|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n* On July 4, 2019, The Santa Clara PD were called near the entrance of the park where a woman was shot during the evening of the fireworks show. The victim was struck on the arm by a handgun. She did not suffer any serious injuries and was also treated at the scene. It was ruled as an altercation between two family groups.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcbayarea.com/news/local/Great-America-Shooting-Suspect-Still-at-Large-512279892.html|title=California's Great America Shooting Suspect Still at Large - NBC Bay Area|publisher=NBC Bay Area|first=Mandela|last=Linder|date=2019-07-05|accessdate=2019-09-25}}</ref>\n* On October 26, 2019, A group of teenagers sparked some firecrackers in the front gate causing guests to scramble, thinking it was a shooting. It was later determined to be due to a robbery. Concession stands within the park were also robbed by fleeing guests. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2019/10/29/details-released-on-false-shooting-report-panic-at-great-america-amusement-park/|title=Details Released On False Shooting Report, Panic At Great America Amusement Park|date=October 29, 2019|work=KPIX 5|accessdate=November 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Notes==\n* Michelson, Herb. (June 7, 1984). \"City will purchase Marriott's\". ''The Sacramento Bee'', p. A.\n* \"Santa Clara drops Great America pact\". (February 7, 1985). ''San Francisco Chronicle'', p.&nbsp;4.\n* Ewell, Miranda. (June 6, 1985). \"Santa Clara assumes ownership of Great America\". ''San Jose Mercury News'' (CA), p.&nbsp;8B.\n* Kava, Brad. (March 15, 1989). \"Great America reopens\". ''San Jose Mercury News'', p.&nbsp;1.\n* Eng, Sherri. (August 1, 1992). \"Paramount to buy Great America owner\". ''San Jose Mercury News'', p.&nbsp;1E.\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|San Francisco Bay Area}}\n{{Commons category}}\n\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://greatamericaparks.com/ Great America parks]&nbsp;\u2013 History of Marriott's Great America\n* {{RCDB|4541}}\n* [https://maps.google.com/maps?q=Santa+Clara,+CA&ll=37.395551,-121.972082&spn=0.010254,0.014473&t=k&hl=en Satellite view of the site]\n\n{{Cedar Fair}}\n{{California's Great America}}\n{{San Jose and Silicon Valley attractions}}\n{{Paramount Parks}}\n{{Amusement Parks & Theme Parks of California}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2012}}\n\n[[Category:California's Great America| ]]\n[[Category:Cedar Fair amusement parks]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks in California]]\n[[Category:1976 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Bay Area amusement parks]]\n[[Category:Economy of Santa Clara, California]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Santa Clara, California]]\n[[Category:Amusement parks opened in 1976]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the theme park in Gurnee, Illinois|Six Flags Great America}}\n{{Infobox amusement park\n| name = California's Great America\n| image = <br>[[File:California's Great America Logo.svg|200px]]<br><br>[[File:California's Great America 2.JPG|240px]]\n| caption = \n| location = [[Santa Clara, California|Santa Clara]] \n| location2 = [[California]]\n| location3 = [[United States]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|37|23|45.4|N|121|58|20.1|W|display=title,inline}}\n| opening_date = {{start date|1976|3|20}}\n| previous_names = '''''Marriott's Great America''''' <span style=\"white-space: nowrap\"> 1976\u20131984</span><br />'''''Great America''''' <span style=\"white-space: nowrap\"> 1985\u20131992, 2007 </span><br />'''''Paramount's Great America''''' <span style=\"white-space: nowrap\"> 1993\u20132006 </span>\n| area = {{convert|100|acre}}\n| season = Late March\u2013December\n| rides = 52\n| coasters = 9\n| water_rides = 2\n| theme = \n| owner = [[Cedar Fair Entertainment Company]]\n| general_manager = Manuel Gonzalez \n| status = Operating\n| slogan = It's Amazing in Here\n| homepage = {{Official website|http://www.cagreatamerica.com}}\n}}\n\n'''California's Great America''' (formerly known as '''Marriott's Great America''' and '''Paramount's Great America''') is a {{convert|100|acre|adj=on}} [[amusement park]] located in [[Santa Clara, California]]. Owned and operated by [[Cedar Fair]], it originally opened in 1976 as one of two parks built by the [[Marriott Corporation]]. The park has appeared in 1994 films ''[[Beverly Hills Cop III]]'' and ''[[Getting Even with Dad]]'' and features over 40 rides and attractions. One of its most notable attractions, [[Gold Striker]], has been featured as a top-ranked wooden roller coaster in ''[[Amusement Today|Amusement Today's]]'' annual Golden Ticket Awards publication. Also featured is Railblazer, one of the first Raptor roller coasters by [Rocky Mountain Construction]] in the World, and Flight Deck, a [Bolliger & Mabillard] inverted coaster.\n\n==History==\n\n===Marriott & KECO Era (1976\u20131992)===\nMarriott's Great America, built by hotel and restaurant operator [[Marriott Corporation]], opened to the public on March 20, 1976.<ref>{{cite news |title=Photos: A look back at 40 years of California's Great America |date=March 27, 2015 |newspaper=San Jose Mercury News |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/2015/03/27/photos-a-look-back-at-40-years-of-californias-great-america/}}</ref> Less than two months later on May 29, the company opened a second Marriott's Great America&nbsp;\u2013 later known as [[Six Flags Great America]]&nbsp;\u2013 north of [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]] in [[Gurnee, Illinois]].<ref name=\"Six Flags purchase\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/04/27/business/marriott-to-sell-park-to-bally.html|title=Marriott to Sell Park to Bally|date=April 27, 1984|newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref> [[Marriott's Great America (Maryland\u2013Virginia)|A third park]] was initially planned for the [[Baltimore\u2013Washington metropolitan area]], but the idea was later abandoned after several failed attempts to sway local opposition.<ref name=\"3rd Great America\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1298&dat=19770819&id=j95NAAAAIBAJ&sjid=-ooDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5660,2451015|title=Marriott's high-powered approach|last=Flattau|first=Edward|date=August 19, 1977|work=The Free Lance-Star|accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Great america.jpg|thumb|left|View of California's Great America from above]]\nThe park, though profitable, was still an earnings disappointment for Marriott, leading the company in 1983 to explore options to sell. An interested party, '''Caz Development Co.''', appraised the land value at US$800,000 to $1 million per acre. Marriott also involved the city of Santa Clara in negotiations, which was already leasing {{convert|55|acre}} of parking space for the amusement park. Fearing homebuilding on the land by Caz Development would lower home values of existing homeowners, the city council approved a $101 million purchasing agreement on January 31, 1984, by a 4\u20133 vote that also had to be approved by city residents. The citywide vote passed, approving the sale by a margin of 3 to 1. Caz Development then sued the city and Marriott in the [[Superior Court of Santa Clara County]] to block the transaction. The court nullified the sale, forcing the city to attempt to salvage the deal through negotiations with the other parties. Unable to broker a timely agreement, the city council voted 6\u20131 to scuttle the sale on February 5, 1985, though the city was still interested in owning the park. After Marriott refunded a $20 million down payment back to the city, negotiations were restarted. All parties were able to agree on a compromise, which was signed in marathon sessions taking place in early June 1985. The city acquired the park for $93.5 million from Marriott, which retained {{convert|20|acre}} from the sale for development. Caz Development settled and was allowed to build a hotel and office near the park, which the city renamed Great America.\n\n[[Kings Entertainment Company]], who owned and operated other amusement parks, was hired in 1985 to manage Great America for the city.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1948&dat=19850620&id=KNZJAAAAIBAJ&sjid=aB0NAAAAIBAJ&pg=1152,5468771|title=A New Start At Great America|date=June 20, 1985|work=The Modesto Bee|accessdate=July 10, 2012|location=Modesto, CA}}</ref> In 1989, the city decided to return the park to the private sector and sold it to Kings Entertainment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1992&dat=19890606&id=W5VcAAAAIBAJ&sjid=IlgNAAAAIBAJ&pg=5086,1057726|title=Firm Acquires Big Theme Park|date=June 6, 1989|work=Merced Sun-Star|accessdate=July 10, 2012|location=Merced, California}}</ref> In the agreement, the city would earn 5% of all revenue that exceeds $56 million.{{Citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\n===Paramount Parks Era (1992\u20132006)===\n[[Image:Paramountgreatamerica.jpg|thumb|right|Logo used from 2003 until its sale to Cedar Fair.]]\nThree years later Paramount Communications (formerly [[Gulf+Western]]), the owners of [[Paramount Pictures]], sought to join other entertainment companies as a theme park owner. The company acquired Kings Entertainment, owner of three parks including Great America, and one other park for $400 million and created [[Paramount Parks]]. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]], the parent of [[Viacom Media Networks|MTV Networks]] (including [[Nickelodeon]]), then bought Paramount in 1994, allowing Nickelodeon theming and merchandise into the park as well. During the Paramount era, attractions from the Action FX Theatre, Nickelodeon Splat City (later Nickelodeon Central), Drop Zone Stunt Tower, Invertigo, and many more modern thrill ride attractions were added in. Because the park is landlocked in the center of Silicon Valley, several rides including the classic train ride and the [[Sky Whirl]], a Marriott's Great America signature attraction, were removed to make way for newer attractions.\n\nIn its last years as a Paramount Park, Great America was co-owned with several broadcasting stations in the Bay Area, including [[KPIX-TV]] and [[KBCW (TV)|KBCW]].\n\n===Cedar Fair Entertainment Company (2006\u2013present)===\n[[Image:Great America 2007.PNG|thumb|right|Logo used in 2006. This logo is still seen on the litter bins in and around California's Great America.]]\nAfter Viacom and [[CBS Corporation]] split, Paramount Parks became part of CBS. The merger did not last long, as CBS announced plans to sell the theme park division.\n\n[[Cedar Fair Entertainment Co.]] announced in May 2006 that they were acquiring the amusement park division from CBS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cedarfair.com/ir/press_releases/index.cfm?current_root=15&mode=story&story_id=77 |title=Press Releases :: Cedar Fair Entertainment Company |publisher=Cedarfair.com |accessdate=2012-06-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060728185503/http://www.cedarfair.com/ir/press_releases/index.cfm?current_root=15&mode=story&story_id=77 |archivedate=July 28, 2006 |df=mdy }}</ref> The transaction included licensing agreements with Nickelodeon and Paramount, providing the park the option to retain its Nickelodeon and Paramount theming for several years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/811532/000081153206000054/0000811532-06-000054-index.htm |title=EDGAR Filing Documents for 0000811532-06-000054 |publisher=Sec.gov |date=2006-06-06 |accessdate=2012-06-04}}</ref>\n\nOn October 25, 2007, Cedar Fair renamed the park '''California's Great America'''. For the 2008 season, the park saw the addition of a [[Huss Rides]] top spin ride called FireFall, a new ice show in the \"Great America Theatre\" (formerly The Paramount Theatre), and the addition of the Halloween Haunt event to the park.<ref>[http://www2.cedarfair.com/greatamerica/news/detail.cfm?item_id=652 Great America | San Francisco's Themed Amusement Park<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071116231626/http://www2.cedarfair.com/GreatAmerica/news/detail.cfm?item_id=652 |date=November 16, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2009, Cedar Fair announced that all the Nickelodeon themed areas would be replaced with ''[[Peanuts]]'' themed areas. In 2010, the newly rethemed [[Planet Snoopy]] opened in the park.\n\nOn January 27, 2011, the park announced Invertigo would be removed and relocated to [[Dorney Park]], another Cedar Fair property.<ref>\n{{cite web |url=http://www.cagreatamerica.com/news/detail.cfm?item_id=1069 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-01-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202070540/http://www.cagreatamerica.com/news/detail.cfm?item_id=1069 |archivedate=February 2, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn September 19, 2011, Cedar Fair confirmed reports that California's Great America would be sold to JMA Ventures, LLC for $70 million in cash. The sale required approval by the City of Santa Clara, and its city council was scheduled to vote on the matter on December 6, 2011. Cedar Fair, which purchased the park in 2006, expected to use the cash proceeds from the sale to reduce its senior secured debt.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cedar Fair to sell California's Great America park for $70 million|url=http://cf.wddnsweb2.wddonline.net/_upload/pressreleases/091911%20-%20definitive%20agmt%20-%20caga.pdf|publisher=Cedar Fair Entertainment Company|accessdate=September 20, 2011|date=September 19, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402164136/http://cf.wddnsweb2.wddonline.net/_upload/pressreleases/091911%20-%20definitive%20agmt%20-%20caga.pdf|archivedate=April 2, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> However, on December 6, 2011, JMA Ventures cancelled its plans to purchase the amusement park.<ref name=\"JMA cancels\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/news/2011/12/06/jma-cancels-70m-california-great.html|title=JMA cancels $70M California Great America purchase|date=December 6, 2011|publisher=Business Journal|accessdate=December 7, 2011}}</ref> In the same announcement, Cedar Fair also verified that a long-term agreement was reached with the [[San Francisco 49ers]] regarding parking and construction of a [[Levi's Stadium|new stadium]] adjacent to Great America.<ref name=\"49ers\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/news/2011/12/06/cedar-fair-niners-jma-great-america.html|title=JMA drops plan to buy Great America, but 49ers stadium plans proceed|last=Young|first=Eric|date=December 6, 2011|publisher=San Francisco Business Times|accessdate=December 10, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.sfexaminer.com/local/2011/12/great-america-remain-current-owners-49er-stadium-spat-averted | title=Great America to remain with current owners; 49er stadium spat averted | publisher=The Examiner | date=December 6, 2011 | accessdate=December 10, 2011 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111213231812/http://www.sfexaminer.com/local/2011/12/great-america-remain-current-owners-49er-stadium-spat-averted | archivedate=December 13, 2011 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Areas and attractions==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=1 style=\"font-size: 90%\"\n|-\n! Intensity rating<ref name=Rating>Ratings assigned per California's Great America, where \"1\" is the least intense and \"5\" is the most. See their {{cite web|url=http://www.miadventure.com/images/uploads/file/MA12-Guest-Assistance-Guide.pdf|title=Guest Assistance Guide|publisher=Michigan's Adventure|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120522173044/http://www.miadventure.com/images/uploads/file/MA12-Guest-Assistance-Guide.pdf|archivedate=May 22, 2012|df=mdy-all}} for more specific details.</ref> <small>''(out of 5)''</small>\n|-\n|{{legend inline|#1CADEA|1 <small>(low)</small>|outline=silver}} {{legend inline|#99DA50|2 <small>(mild)</small>|outline=silver}} {{legend inline|#FED530|3 <small>(moderate)</small>|outline=silver}} {{legend inline|#F7B754|4 <small>(high) </small>|outline=silver}} {{legend inline|#ED5B33|5 <small>(aggressive)</small>|outline=silver}}\n|-\n|}\n''Note: Number ratings assigned per California's Great America, while the colors are unique 